  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A Heisenberg uniqueness pair is a pair <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="true">(</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Γ</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi><mo stretchy="true">)</mo></math> , where Γ is a curve and Λ is a set in <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> such that whenever a finite Borel measure μ having support on Γ which is absolutely continuous with respect to the arc length on Γ satisfies <math altimg="si266.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">ˆ</mo></mrow></mover><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">|</mo></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> , then it is identically 0. In this article, we investigate the Heisenberg uniqueness pairs corresponding to the spiral, hyperbola, circle and certain exponential curves. Further, we work out a characterization of the Heisenberg uniqueness pairs corresponding to four parallel lines. In the latter case, we observe a phenomenon of interlacing of three trigonometric polynomials.</subfield>
